{
  "text": "Let us start by discussing the Abelian Higgs model. If we imagine having initially a uniform magnetic field B = B 0 in the system, we know very well from superconductor experiments what happens when we cool it into the broken (superconducting) phase [CITATION_1] : The magnetic field forms a lattice of vortices. Because all the flux must go into the vortices, the number density would be n = (e/2π)|B 0 |. This happens no matter how slowly we cool the system, and therefore the formation of these defects is clearly not described by the Kibble mechanism.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "120168412"
  },
